<div id="review_55201465" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/55201465" />
    <a title="Ron Corio" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2092114-ron-corio"><img alt="Ron Corio" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1236113479p2/2092114.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/55201465?book_show_action=true">May 06, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ron Corio" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ron Corio" href="/user/show/2092114-ron-corio">Ron Corio</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer55201465" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15412423340090020674">We read this book in an Advanced Reading class that I taught for the Spring session. This was the second or third time that I have used this book in a reading class, and with each read it reveals more to me and increases my appreciation of Ernest Gaines&apos; writing.<br/><br/>Gaines&apos; device of using different narrators for each chapter gives this book a layered perspective of the events that happen over one day on a Louisiana sugar cane plantation in the nineteen seventies. Gaines knows his subject, Southwest</span>
  <span id="freeText15412423340090020674" style="display:none">We read this book in an Advanced Reading class that I taught for the Spring session. This was the second or third time that I have used this book in a reading class, and with each read it reveals more to me and increases my appreciation of Ernest Gaines' writing.<br /><br />Gaines' device of using different narrators for each chapter gives this book a layered perspective of the events that happen over one day on a Louisiana sugar cane plantation in the nineteen seventies. Gaines knows his subject, Southwestern Louisiana and its people, well.<br /><br />After a couple of chapters the students became interested in the story and often commented that they wanted to read beyond the assignment in order to find out what happens next.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15412423340090020674" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


